End-to-End Near Real-Time Data Pipeline Architecture
¶

Explain the Flow
¶

Overview¶

The designed architecture enables a near real-time data pipeline that ingests, processes, and analyzes data from multiple sources including web-scraped data, internal sales transactions, mobile app logs, and manually collected market data.The solution ensures continuous data flow, data quality, and scalability using modern data engineering tools.

Contents¶

  1. Why Each Component Was Chosen
  2. How I Handled Streaming and Batch Data Together
  3. How Data Quality and Schema Evolution Are Managed

1- Why Each Component Was Chosen:-
¶

1- Why PostgreSQL Was Chosen (with Debezium + Kafka)¶

  • PostgreSQL was chosen because its (open-source, reliable, CDC-friendly, and seamlessly integrates with Debezium and Kafka).
  • providing a stable transactional source for real-time data streaming.

2- Debezium — Change Data Capture (CDC)¶

  • Continuously capture every change happening in operational databases (inserts, updates, deletes) and stream those changes in real-time to Kafka topics and ensuring the analytics system always has the latest data.
  • Seamless Kafka integration because built on top of Kafka Connect, so it easily plugs into your Kafka cluster.
  • Automatically detects schema changes and updates event structures accordingly.

3- Apache Kafka¶

  • Kafka is designed as a distributed event streaming platform a realtime message broker that moves data between systems quickly and reliably.
  • Handles millions of messages per second with millisecond latency.
  • All data is stored persistently across multiple brokers and partitions, ensuring zero data loss.
  • Horizontally scalable can grow easily by adding more brokers and partitions.
  • Supports replication and automatic failover across clusters.

4- Apache Flink¶

  • Apache Flink was chosen because it delivers ( sub-second latency,true real-time, fault-tolerant, and exactly-once stream processing).
  • perfectly fitting between Kafka (data transport) and Snowflake (data warehouse) in a modern streaming architecture.
  • Optimized for ( high-throughput**, low-latency workloads, and scales horizontally across clusters).

5- DBT¶

  • Allows to write data transformations using SQL, making it simple, readable, and easy for teams who already know SQL, with no complex ETL coding required
  • Its modular design allows for scalability as data needs grow.
  • Automated data testing ensures accuracy and reliability in data pipelines.
  • Comprehensive documentation and lineage tracking enhance data governance.
  • DBT integrates with Git for effective version control and collaboration.

6- Snowflake¶

  • Snowflake handles all infrastructure scaling, optimization, and storage, allowing the team to focus on data pipelines and analytics, rather than cluster management.
  • Snowflake automatically scales up or down to handle varying workloads.
  • Data is stored in a compressed columnar format with intelligent caching.
  • Enabling fast query performance even on massive datasets.

2- How I Handled Streaming and Batch Data Together
¶

Handling Streaming Data¶

  • I used PostgreSQL + Debezium + Kafka + Flink** to build the real-time data stream.
  • Debezium captured database changes instantly using CDC from PostgreSQL WAL logs.
  • These changes were pushed into Kafka topics, which acted as a high-throughput event bus.
  • Flink consumed events from Kafka, performed aggregations and enrichments in real-time,and pushed results into Snowflake for immediate availability.

Goal:---> Low-latency data delivery for real-time dashboards and operational analytics.

Handling Batch Data¶

  • I handled large historical or scheduled datasets through ETL/ELT pipelines using Airflow and dbt.
  • These pipelines periodically pulled raw data (daily/hourly) into Snowflake,where dbt handled SQL-based transformations, quality checks, and model building.

Goal:---> Ensure completeness, heavy transformations, and accurate long-term reporting.

Integration Strategy¶

  • Both streaming and batch data end up in Snowflake,
    which serves as the single source of truth for analytics.
  • dbt is used on top of Snowflake to apply unified transformations, ensuring that both real-time and batch datasets share the same business logic and schema.
  • This setup provides a hybrid data architecture that combines:
    • Freshness from streaming
    • Accuracy and historical depth from batch

3- How Data Quality and Schema Evolution Are Managed
¶

1. Data Quality Management¶

Validation and Testing with dbt

  • Implemented dbt tests (both generic and custom) to validate data after ingestion.
  • Checks include:
    • Uniqueness (no duplicate primary keys)
    • Not null (critical columns always populated)
    • Referential integrity (foreign keys match)
    • Accepted values and ranges (e.g., status codes, amounts)
  • dbt also provides test results and alerts in CI/CD pipelines for continuous monitoring.

Monitoring at the Stream Level (Flink / Kafka) using Grafana

  • Used Flink metrics and Kafka lag monitoring to ensure data completeness and timeliness.
  • Implemented validation operators in Flink to catch malformed or missing events before they reach Snowflake.

2. Schema Evolution¶

1️- Source Layer — PostgreSQL¶

When any schema change happens in PostgreSQL for example:

  • Adding a new column (ADD COLUMN)
  • Dropping a column (DROP COLUMN)
  • Changing a data type (ALTER TYPE)
  • Renaming a column (RENAME COLUMN)

PostgreSQL automatically records this change in the Write-Ahead Log (WAL).
Debezium continuously reads this log to detect both data and schema changes in real time.

No manual tracking needed WAL captures every structural change automatically.

2️- Change Capture Layer — Debezium¶

Debezium monitors the WAL and detects any schema modifications immediately.
When a change occurs, Debezium:

  • Extracts the new schema definition from PostgreSQL.
  • Publishes a new schema version along with change events to Kafka topics.
  • Includes both the data payload and the schema metadata in each message.

This ensures that every Kafka event carries the current schema, so downstream systems always stay in sync.

3️- Schema Management — Kafka Schema Registry¶

The Schema Registry stores all versions of the schemas received from Debezium. Each schema version is assigned a unique version number and compatibility rule:

  • If the new schema is compatible (e.g., adding a nullable field), it is accepted.
  • If it introduces a breaking change (e.g., removing a required column or changing a data type), it is rejected.

This guarantees that downstream systems like Flink or Snowflake never break due to incompatible schema updates.

4️- Stream Processing Layer — Flink¶

Flink integrates directly with the Schema Registry.
When new schema versions arrive:

  • For minor changes (like adding optional fields), Flink adapts automatically or ignores the new fields.
  • For major changes (like changing field types), a controlled job redeployment is triggered with the updated schema.

This provides flexibility pipelines remain stable even as the schema evolves upstream.

5️- Data Warehouse Layer — Snowflake + dbt¶

When events are written to Snowflake (via Kafka Connect or Flink sink):

  • If Auto Schema Evolution is enabled, Snowflake automatically adds new columns.
  • Otherwise, schema updates are managed manually through dbt models (version-controlled in Git).
  • dbt ensures that all transformations and downstream analytical models stay consistent with the latest schema.

Snowflake and dbt keep the warehouse synchronized with upstream schema changes safely.
